defaultIn all of my researc
defaulth a fundamental aspect is being able to discuss these issues 
defaultat a grass roots level 
defaultwith young people themselves. While we might have additional data collection mechanisms such as survey work, the core of any research project will be sitting with young peo
defaultple, usually in groups, talking about the research questions and their thoughts. This is all conducted within a clear ethicial framework working alongside schools to place the young people in a safe, non-judgemental environment where they are free to share
default opinions and reflections without being challenged or confronted. Parental consent is obtained for any young people spoken 
defaultto,
default they are fully briefed on the research context, and have the right to withdraw from the discussions at any time. 
defaultWhile these disc
defaultussions can sometimes centre on difficult issues, such as sexting, pornography and 
defaultgender, I usually find the discussions very open and productive (we don’t ask young people to disclose about their own behaviour, but to ref
defaultlect on the behaviour of peers). 
defaultI also work with stakeholders in the online safety area, such as parents, teachers and social care professionals to understand their attitudes and concerns related to online safety and young people. 
defaultA recent example of this work was a piece of research con
defaultducted by the NSPCC/UK Safer Internet Centre around sexting
