defaultPreventing abusive or threatening commdefaultents on social media.defaultFinally, while it is good to see an Parliamentary committee looking at this issue, because when I talk to young people about online issues cyberbullying (or simply “people being mean”) is by far the most likely response whe
defaultn I ask what upsets them online, I would, again, take issue with the wording used. Put simply, you will never 
defaultprevent
default abusive or threatening comments on social media, just 
defaultas
default you will never prevent nasty comments in the playground, on TV shows such as the X Factor, on the football pitch
default or at PMQs
default. However, far more can be done to provide an environment where young people should know they do not have to put up with this sort o
defaultf thing and that 
defaultpeople can
default help. I should stress, first of all, that it is rare that a young person will talk about “cyberbullying” and the term is unhelpful when trying to address the problems caused by people being abusive online. Online abuse can be de
defaultscribed in many forms, such as nastiness, people being mean, calling names, ganging up or simply banter and again 
defaultequitability is difficult to manage in this area – one young person
default’
defaults banter will be considered abuse by another. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, it is important t
defaulthat services providers 
defaultoffer
default the means to report abuse, something that is 
defaultalready in place
default by some social media platforms but not others. Young people also need to be aware that they can use these reporting mechanisms to take comments down and also they wi
defaultll not get into trouble themselves. The wording of some reporting functions is intimidating and can be overwhelming for young people. 
default&#xa0;
defaultBut, once again, education is the pivotal player in this area – education around 
defaultwhat
default is and isn’t acceptable language, 
defaultthe impact of abuse on others, 
defaultthe disconnect
default and perceived anonymity the Internet provides, and the potential 
defaultil
defaultlegality of some forms of abuse. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is also encouraging to see some discussion from the Director of Public Prosecutions and Crown Prosecution
default Service around this 
defaultissue,
default it is helpful to get some clarification on abusive language. It is also encouraging to see it stated it is rarely in the public interest for minors to be prosecuted for this sort of thing.
default&#xa0;
defaultI have seen a number of schools adopti
defaultng a restorative justice approach to the resolution of online abuse issues and this makes sense – in a lot of cases the perpetrator will not be aware of the impact of their words on the victim and to place them in an environment where they can hear about i
defaultt is a powerful one. However, it is important the restorative justice is implemented effectively with trained counselors – it is not something that can be done effectively without experienced professionals. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultIn summary, it is encouraging to see this inqu
defaultiry exploring some of the broader issues around online safety and not just focus on the headline grabbing ones. However, it is still a concern that a lot of the language focuses on prevention and filtering rather than education and awareness. The Internet 
defaultis not something that can be “policed” with technology. If we wish to protect young people and help them protect 
defaultthemselves, we can
defaultnot 
defaultlay
default responsibility 
defaultsolely on 
defaultservice providers and software just as we cannot blame the Royal Mail for delivering an unwa
defaultnted letter. We need parents to be aware of issues, we need education professionals to be able and allowed to provide an effective environment to both learn about and talk about these issues, and we need policy makers who are awareness of the broad context
default of online safety and the complexities of growing up in the digital age.  
